    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-06-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-06-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="372"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                <head>372. National Security Study Memorandum 130<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d372fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–185, National Security Study Memoranda, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 130. Secret. A copy was sent to the
                        Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-06-18">June 18, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director, Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Cyprus Planning</item>
                </list>
                <pb facs="0949" n="905" xml:id="pg_905"/>
                <p>The President has directed a review of our policy toward Cyprus in the light of
                    recent changes in the situation. A paper should be prepared under the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSCIG1">NSCIG</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> which
                    would explicitly address: <list>
                        <item>—likely developments in the situation with which the <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> may be confronted;</item>
                        <item>—the effects of those developments on <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                >U.S.</gloss> interests; <hi rend="italic">and</hi>
                        </item>
                        <item>—the options open to the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> in each
                            possible situation.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This should be submitted to the Senior Review Group by July 2, 1971.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d372fn2">See <ref target="#d375">Document 375</ref>. According to a
                        June 14 memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Saunders</persName> to
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SH1">Saunders</persName> would prepare a similar study for
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>. (National Archives,
                            <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Material,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 592, Country Files—Middle
                        East, Cyprus, Vol. I Jan 1969–June 30, 1974)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
